## The Foundation: Intent + State + Constraints

Every Cursor prompt needs all three layers. Missing one causes hallucinations, scope drift, or wrong fixes.

| Layer | What It Is | Without It |
|---|---|---|
| **Intent** | What you want to achieve | Cursor guesses the goal |
| **State** | Which files are relevant right now | Cursor searches blind, misses context |
| **Constraints** | What must NOT change | Cursor "improves" unrelated things and breaks them |

**Structure every prompt like this:**
```
[CONSTRAINT UPFRONT: what not to touch]
[Intent: what you want]
[State: @file1 @file2 — the exact relevant files]
[Constraint repeated at end: confirm scope]
```

> Why constraints at top AND bottom? Research shows LLMs give highest attention to the first and last parts of context. The middle gets "lost." Bury your key constraint in the middle and Cursor may ignore it.

